SQL queries databases, WebQL scrapes websites. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://shop.com/electronics",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product' and contains(@data-category, 'electronics')]",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3[@class='title']/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- SQL: SELECT/FROM/WHERE syntax
- WebQL: JSON with @url/@steps/@xpath/@fields
- SQL: Database queries
- WebQL: HTML scraping

GraphQL queries APIs with schemas, WebQL scrapes HTML. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com/products",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//h3[@class='name']/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()",
        "description": ".//p[@class='description']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- GraphQL: query { field { subfield } } syntax
- WebQL: JSON with @url/@steps/@xpath/@fields
- GraphQL: API with predefined schema
- WebQL: Direct HTML element extraction

MongoDB queries databases, WebQL scrapes websites. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://bookstore.com/books?max_price=20",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='book' and .//span[@class='price' and number(translate(text(), '$', '')) < 20]]",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3[@class='title']/text()",
        "category": ".//span[@class='category']/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- MongoDB: db.collection.find() syntax
- WebQL: JSON with @url/@steps/@xpath/@fields
- MongoDB: Database documents
- WebQL: HTML elements

REST APIs return structured data, WebQL scrapes HTML. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com/users?role=admin&status=active",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='user' and contains(@data-role, 'admin') and contains(@data-status, 'active')]",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//span[@class='name']/text()",
        "role": ".//span[@class='role']/text()",
        "status": ".//span[@class='status']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- REST: HTTP GET /api/endpoint
- WebQL: JSON with @url/@steps/@xpath/@fields
- REST: JSON/XML responses
- WebQL: HTML scraping with XPath

CSS selectors target elements, WebQL needs complete structure. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3[@class='title']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- CSS: .product h3.title (element selection)
- WebQL: XPath //div[@class='product'] + .//h3[@class='title']/text()
- CSS: Just selects elements
- WebQL: Complete extraction framework with URL, steps, fields

Raw XPath selects elements, WebQL needs complete structure. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- XPath: //div[@class='product']//h3/text() (element selection)
- WebQL: @xpath for containers + @fields for data extraction
- XPath: Just path expression
- WebQL: Complete scraping framework with URL, actions, steps

Python code is imperative, WebQL is declarative. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- Python: Imperative programming (soup.find_all())
- WebQL: Declarative configuration (JSON structure)
- Python: Code execution
- WebQL: Data-driven extraction

jQuery manipulates DOM, WebQL extracts data. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "title": ".//h3/text()"
      }
    }
