Key differences:
- jQuery: $('.product').find('h3').text() (DOM manipulation)
- WebQL: XPath //div[@class='product'] + .//h3/text()
- jQuery: Browser-based scripting
- WebQL: Server-side data extraction

cURL fetches API data, WebQL scrapes HTML. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com/products",
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//h3/text()",
        "id": "./@data-id"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- cURL: HTTP client for APIs (Accept: application/json)
- WebQL: HTML scraper (extracts from rendered pages)
- cURL: Command-line tool
- WebQL: Declarative query language

Selenium controls browsers, WebQL declares extraction. WebQL equivalent:

{
  "@url": "https://example.com",
  "@actions": [
    {
      "@type": "wait",
      "@until": "element",
      "@selector": ".product",
      "@timeout": 5000
    }
  ],
  "@steps": [
    {
      "@xpath": "//div[@class='product']",
      "@fields": {
        "name": ".//h3/text()",
        "price": ".//span[@class='price']/text()"
      }
    }
  ]
}

Key differences:
- Selenium: Imperative browser automation
- WebQL: Declarative data extraction
- Selenium: Programming code
- WebQL: Configuration-based
